{"accepted":[{"assertion":"AI-contributions wiki claim — wiki: Partial result.","id":"vf_49949f2f238f3335","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Formal-Conjectures statement: Erdos503.erdos_503 https://google-deepmind.github.io/formal-conjectures/theorem/?name=Erdos503.erdos_503.","id":"vf_7a1ac938f232d81d","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"},{"assertion":"Erdős Problem #503: declared status 'open'. Formalized: yes. What is the size of the largest $A\\subseteq \\mathbb{R}^d$ such that every three points from $A$ determine an isosceles triangle? That is, for any three points $x,y,z$ from $A$, at least two of the distances $\\lvert x-y\\rvert,\\lvert y-z\\rvert,\\lvert x-z\\rvert$ are equal. Current best: The best upper bound known in general is due to Blokhuis \\cite{Bl84} who showed that\\[\\lvert A\\rvert \\leq \\binom{d+2}{2}.\\]Alweiss has observed a lower bound of $\\binom{d+1}{2}$ follows from considering the subset of $\\mathbb{R}^{d+1}$ formed of all vectors $e_i+e_j$ where $e_i,e_j$ are distinct coordinate vectors. Weisenberg observed in the comments that an additional point can be added to Alweiss' construction, giving a lower bound of $\\binom{d+1}{2}+1$. Prize: no. OEIS: A175769. Tags: distances, geometry.","id":"vf_e4e6ab7c06c15530","trust":"signed","type":"theoretical"}],"accepted_activity":false,"activity":[],"activity_types":[],"attempt_count":0,"banked_attempt_count":0,"commits":[],"dependency_impact":"none","detail_url":"problems/503.json","draft_proposals":[],"edges":[{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_49949f2f238f3335","source_root":"sha256:1faedc24f040a60a22177b456c74b969a61ce8836082297b1835797a57b4fa56","target":"erdos:503","trust":"signed"},{"evidence":"Problem identity derived from the accepted finding's pinned source anchor.","inferred":true,"relation":"describes","source":"vf_7a1ac938f232d81d","source_root":"sha256:1fae